FLORENCE ION: It's also nice
to be able to go back and fix,

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:21.700
if you are rushing through
some dialog windows,

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:24.442
to make sure that maybe the
camera is no longer accessible.

00:10:24.442 --> 00:10:25.900
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Right, exactly.

00:10:25.900 --> 00:10:27.130
FLORENCE ION: Or
your location, too,

00:10:27.130 --> 00:10:28.590
which is another big
feature of Android.

00:10:28.590 --> 00:10:29.290
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
No, that's great.

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:30.415
Yeah, so those are exactly.

00:10:30.415 --> 00:10:32.110
Those are, as you
point out, those

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:33.550
are the screens
that we've added,

00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:36.130
so that you can go back and
audit and say, OK, what did I?

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:37.510
Who did I give permission to do?

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:38.140
What again?

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:39.517
And you can decide.

00:10:39.517 --> 00:10:41.100
Maybe that doesn't
make sense anymore.

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:42.620
And at least,
there's transparency,

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:43.810
and then there's controls.

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:44.852
FLORENCE ION: Absolutely.

00:10:44.852 --> 00:10:47.600
So being that this is
a crowd of developers,

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:49.250
and we have a lot
tuning in right now,

00:10:49.250 --> 00:10:52.540
what should they know about
these new privacy and security

00:10:52.540 --> 00:10:56.212
features and about implementing
them into their apps?

00:10:56.212 --> 00:10:58.420
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: In terms
of technology, you mean?

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:01.690
FLORENCE ION: Just in terms of
making it friendly for users

00:11:01.690 --> 00:11:02.950
who are coming to Android.

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:04.240
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah,
I think that's a key point.

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:06.550
I mean, some of these
things are obvious, I think.

00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:10.620
But don't do things that
you don't need to do.

00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:12.460
A lot of times--

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:15.010
we do this at Google, too,
where we'll be like, well, maybe

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:16.630
eventually we'll
want this permission,

00:11:16.630 --> 00:11:18.470
or maybe eventually we'll
want to be able to do this,

00:11:18.470 --> 00:11:20.080
or you asked for these
capability right.

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:22.663
But if you're actually not going
to need it, don't ask for it.

00:11:22.663 --> 00:11:25.150
Because otherwise, the user
is going to be confused, too,

00:11:25.150 --> 00:11:26.658
and it's just unnecessary.

00:11:26.658 --> 00:11:29.200
So things like that, just being
really thoughtful and mindful

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:33.190
about what you're
trying to do, or trying

00:11:33.190 --> 00:11:36.130
to scope as much as
possible the access

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:38.650
to the bare minimum of what you
need, I think, is important.

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:40.330
Because people do
notice this stuff,

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:43.240
and it is an important part
of how people, I think,

00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:46.700
also decide whether they want
to use an app, versus another.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:47.200
Yeah.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.610
FLORENCE ION: I like that
idea of mindful developing.

00:11:49.610 --> 00:11:51.310
I feel like that's
a good [INAUDIBLE]..

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:53.060
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Just out of curiosity,

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:57.050
how many in the crowd, how many
of you are Android developers?

00:11:57.050 --> 00:11:58.240
Well, OK, most of you?

00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:00.190
Web?

00:12:00.190 --> 00:12:01.390
Yeah, a lot of you also.

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:04.320
OK, other platforms?

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.120
Yeah, well, a good mix.

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:07.750
FLORENCE ION: Yeah,
that's a good mix.

00:12:07.750 --> 00:12:13.020
So you manage more
than just Android.

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:18.250
You are also overseeing a Play,
and you're overseeing Chome OS.

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:21.220
How do you try to keep
the ecosystems on track?

00:12:21.220 --> 00:12:23.290
Is there a shared
ethos or philosophy

00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:26.560
that helps drive the
decisions that you all

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:28.770
are making as a team?

00:12:28.770 --> 00:12:30.820
And how do you
ensure that you stick

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:33.850
to that philosophy or that
ethos with every new release

00:12:33.850 --> 00:12:34.930
of Android.?

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:37.543
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah,
I think one of the--

00:12:37.543 --> 00:12:39.460
I'm going to make it
sound very dramatic-- one

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:43.090
of the key insights that we
have is that you all are busy,

00:12:43.090 --> 00:12:44.740
and you have a lot
of things to do,

00:12:44.740 --> 00:12:47.800
and you have your own
plans and own roadmaps

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.050
and own priorities and
maybe your own bosses.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:51.760
Maybe your own boss,
but you have bosses

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:53.300
who have other priorities.

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:55.030
So the last thing
you want to deal with

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:57.310
is the platform
provider telling you

00:12:57.310 --> 00:12:59.520
what your priorities should be.

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:01.580
So we try to minimize
that as much as possible.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:03.280
Obviously, whenever
we change platforms,

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:05.260
we realize we introduce
work for you--

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:07.390
opportunities, too.

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:09.118
So there's a balance there.

00:13:09.118 --> 00:13:11.410
So that's one of the things
that we think about deeply.

00:13:11.410 --> 00:13:16.690
So keeping that in mind,
to answer your question,

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:19.990
across Android and
Chrome OS, for instance,

00:13:19.990 --> 00:13:23.860
I see Play as being
one unifying ecosystem.

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:25.610
You can run, as
many of you know,

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:28.300
you can run Android apps
on many Chromebooks now.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:30.770
And that's going to continue.

00:13:30.770 --> 00:13:33.580
And that's a way for you
to have your investment,

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:37.030
like in this example,
in an Android app,

00:13:37.030 --> 00:13:39.790
be useful in the context
of a different form factor,

00:13:39.790 --> 00:13:42.400
even a different
platform, Chrome OS.

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:45.340
And so we're sharing as
much technology as possible

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:48.160
and making it so that,
when you do your work,

00:13:48.160 --> 00:13:53.290
it is useful in as many surfaces
or in as many ways as possible.

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:54.880
That's one of the key things.

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.797
You're asking, how do
we think about all this?

00:13:56.797 --> 00:13:58.540
That's a key thing
we think about.

00:13:58.540 --> 00:13:59.710
We also focus a lot--

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:01.252
I was talking to
Steph the other day,

00:14:01.252 --> 00:14:04.520
and she was talking about how
it's really important for us--

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.630
and we're not always successful
in doing this, especially as

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:09.940
the industry evolves,
but as much as possible,

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:11.930
to keep compatibility.

00:14:11.930 --> 00:14:14.710
So that APIs you rely
on today will still

00:14:14.710 --> 00:14:17.082
be reliable two years from now.

00:14:17.082 --> 00:14:18.790
Obviously, sometimes
we're not able to do

00:14:18.790 --> 00:14:19.748
that, especially with--

00:14:19.748 --> 00:14:22.495
SNS call log is a
perfect example.

00:14:22.495 --> 00:14:24.370
But that's something
that's important for us,

00:14:24.370 --> 00:14:26.920
because we know that's
important for you, as well.

00:14:26.920 --> 00:14:29.290
And also just
having great tools--

00:14:29.290 --> 00:14:31.780
you saw us investing in--

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:34.818
a lot of you are Android
developers, so the [INAUDIBLE]..

00:14:34.818 --> 00:14:36.610
We're bringing Android
Studio to Chrome OS.

00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:38.230
We announced that
here and made it

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:40.838
really easy for people
to download these tools

00:14:40.838 --> 00:14:41.380
and use them.

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:45.610
So those are also areas that
we're investing a ton in.

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:47.380
FLORENCE ION: So as
a platform, Android

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:50.500
has been very open
for a very long time.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:53.450
Do you feel like it's a delicate
balancing act to just getting

00:14:53.450 --> 00:14:58.330
OEMs and others to adhere to
exactly what Android is trying

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:01.017
to do for mobile computing?

00:15:01.017 --> 00:15:02.350
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah, it is.

00:15:02.350 --> 00:15:04.755
We have literally hundreds
and hundreds of OES.

00:15:04.755 --> 00:15:06.880
FLORENCE ION: Literally
hundreds and hundreds, yes.

00:15:06.880 --> 00:15:10.210
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yes, and
many hundreds and hundreds

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:11.800
of operators
throughout the world,

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:17.690
and many, many, many developers,
you around the world, as well.

00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:22.042
So it's this melting
pot of a lot of--

00:15:22.042 --> 00:15:24.250
I mean, we're all interested
in the same thing, which

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:27.610
is being successful
in our businesses

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:30.002
and building creative,
innovative things

00:15:30.002 --> 00:15:31.210
and bringing it to consumers.

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:32.740
I think that's what
we're all about,

00:15:32.740 --> 00:15:34.102
if I were to simplify it.

00:15:34.102 --> 00:15:36.310
But we all have different
motivations and different--

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:37.360
we play different roles.

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:38.193
FLORENCE ION: Right.

00:15:38.193 --> 00:15:41.500
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: And so we
see, as a platform provider,

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:44.740
we see our role as
being the party that

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:48.430
brings a lot of these
perspectives together.

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:50.360
And sometimes they
don't always line up.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:54.820
And even, just in
the OEM space, if you

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:56.930
think about we work
closely with Samsung,

00:15:56.930 --> 00:15:59.770
we work closely with LG, we work
closely with the pixel team--

00:15:59.770 --> 00:16:01.690
who, by the way,
we treat as a OEM.

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:05.830
We treat them as just another
OEM alongside Samsung and LG.

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:09.260
And you name how ever many
OEMs there are in the world,

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:12.430
and they all compete with
each other, these OEMs.

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:15.040
And so they share
their secrets with us,

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:18.310
and we're careful not to share
their secrets with anyone else,

00:16:18.310 --> 00:16:19.750
because they're trusting us.

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:21.240
And they have
different opinions.

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.740
And so then it becomes our job
to try to figure out the best

00:16:23.740 --> 00:16:25.308
way to navigate that.

00:16:25.308 --> 00:16:27.100
And I think that's the
same for developers,

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:28.900
the same for operators.

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:30.670
And so we spend a lot of--

00:16:30.670 --> 00:16:32.645
I mentioned earlier,
when you asked me

00:16:32.645 --> 00:16:35.020
what my typical day is, and
I said, I spend a lot of time

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:35.603
with partners.

00:16:35.603 --> 00:16:38.380
That's part of the
reason, is to understand

00:16:38.380 --> 00:16:40.270
everyone's
perspectives, understand

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:43.840
what's important for you and for
the operator and for the OEM,

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:46.750
and try to bring it
together that way.

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:47.410
It's fun.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:47.950
It's fun.

00:16:47.950 --> 00:16:49.492
Sundar sometimes
says, you're kind of

00:16:49.492 --> 00:16:50.760
like the United Nations.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:52.510
I've never worked with
the United Nations.

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:53.450
I don't know what that's like.

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:55.173
But I assume-- at least,
I don't know if he has.

00:16:55.173 --> 00:16:55.940
FLORENCE ION: I hear
it's a very hard job.

00:16:55.940 --> 00:16:57.440
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Yeah, but that's

00:16:57.440 --> 00:16:59.080
what it seems like sometimes.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:00.107
But it's fun.

00:17:00.107 --> 00:17:01.690
FLORENCE ION: When
did you guys decide

00:17:01.690 --> 00:17:04.589
that you were going to
you just make Android work

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:06.109
on foldable displays?

00:17:06.109 --> 00:17:08.170
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah,
well that, again, that

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:12.099
came up because Samsung--

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:14.526
but Samsung wasn't the only one.

00:17:14.526 --> 00:17:17.109
There are many OEMs, some which
have been announced, some that

00:17:17.109 --> 00:17:18.119
haven't been announced yet.

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:20.577
FLORENCE ION: I mean, this was
going around for years, it's

00:17:20.577 --> 00:17:21.700
been, this idea.

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:24.619
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah, this
idea, and now it's possible.

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:29.362
And so a lot of OEMs have
approached us over the years.

00:17:29.362 --> 00:17:31.570
Another example of this, if
you talk about foldables,

00:17:31.570 --> 00:17:34.540
but now it seems like
all phones are like this.

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:38.590
But just a few years ago, the
aspect ratio of most phones

00:17:38.590 --> 00:17:39.960
were more sort of square.

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:41.200
They became taller.

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:42.910
They grew notches.

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:45.010
Do you grow a notch, or
do you subtract a not--

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:46.780
I don't know what
direction a notch goes.

00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:50.380
But those are all things
that happened roughly

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:52.502
at the same time for
the whole industry,

00:17:52.502 --> 00:17:54.460
because that's just how
the supply chain works.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:57.190
These vendors who
build displays are

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:58.990
able to do this,
and then the OEMs,

00:17:58.990 --> 00:18:00.590
the manufacturers
buy these displays.

00:18:00.590 --> 00:18:03.350
So that's why they roughly
happen at the same time.

00:18:03.350 --> 00:18:06.310
And so foldables, I think,
will follow a similar pattern,

00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:09.730
where these display technologies
are now there for OEMs

00:18:09.730 --> 00:18:12.440
to adopt in their products.

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:15.490
So in the case of foldables,
they approached us, saying,

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:16.310
we want to do this.

00:18:16.310 --> 00:18:18.640
We think we can do it now.

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:21.400
We're worried about
the ecosystem impact.

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:23.740
By ecosystem here,
the OEMs were talking

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:25.532
about you, the developers.

00:18:25.532 --> 00:18:27.490
They wanted to make sure
this was easy for you.

00:18:27.490 --> 00:18:30.970
They wanted your apps to work
really well on their devices,

00:18:30.970 --> 00:18:33.215
hopefully with no work from you.

00:18:33.215 --> 00:18:35.590
That's always the hope, is
that you don't want developers

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:37.270
to have to do work.

00:18:37.270 --> 00:18:39.367
Because, again, you have
your own work to do.

00:18:39.367 --> 00:18:41.700
Why should you have to do
special work for someone else?

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:44.080
That's how they think about it.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:47.830
And so we work really
closely together with them

00:18:47.830 --> 00:18:50.920
on figuring out, how
can we use existing APIs

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:52.740
and make them work that way?

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:56.170
And by the way, just to go
back to one of your earlier

00:18:56.170 --> 00:18:57.863
questions, there's
a nice benefit here,

00:18:57.863 --> 00:18:59.530
too, because a lot
of that work that you

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:01.330
may be doing for
foldables will be

00:19:01.330 --> 00:19:04.433
useful for Chrome OS
your app on Chrome OS,

00:19:04.433 --> 00:19:06.100
because re-sizeable
apps and things like

00:19:06.100 --> 00:19:07.140
that are very useful.

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:09.140
So again, it's kind of a
two birds, three birds,

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.130
one stone type of moment.

00:19:11.130 --> 00:19:12.130
That's what we live for.

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:12.860
We like that.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:14.860
FLORENCE ION: I do want
to talk about Chrome OS.

00:19:14.860 --> 00:19:18.490
But before we go there, I want
to ask, what foldable phone are

00:19:18.490 --> 00:19:20.972
you using these days?

00:19:20.972 --> 00:19:22.930
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: I
didn't bring it on stage,

00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:24.940
but I am using a Fold still.

00:19:24.940 --> 00:19:25.810
FLORENCE ION: OK.

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:28.473
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: And I
was actually with some folks

00:19:28.473 --> 00:19:30.640
with the press, and they
were a little bit surprised

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:31.557
that I still have one.

00:19:31.557 --> 00:19:33.723
The reason why I still have
one is because, well, we

00:19:33.723 --> 00:19:34.870
work closely with Samsung.

00:19:34.870 --> 00:19:35.290
FLORENCE ION: You're testing it.

00:19:35.290 --> 00:19:35.620
You're working on it.

00:19:35.620 --> 00:19:38.078
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: I'm making
sure these APIs are working,

00:19:38.078 --> 00:19:38.867
and so on.

00:19:38.867 --> 00:19:39.700
But it's really fun.

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:40.840
Actually, I really like it.

00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:44.113
Let's set aside manufacturing
and et cetera for a second--

00:19:44.113 --> 00:19:46.280
FLORENCE ION: Yeah, let's
talk about folding phones.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:46.360
That's a new concept for us.

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:51.330
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah, it's
really interesting for me.

00:19:51.330 --> 00:19:54.640
I found that I'm much more
intentional about when I

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:56.530
use my phone, which surprised--

00:19:56.530 --> 00:19:58.760
I didn't expect that.

00:19:58.760 --> 00:20:02.890
I thought foldable equals
more screens, bigger screens,

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:04.720
so I'm going to get
lost in my phone more.

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:06.470
But it's actually had
the opposite effect,

00:20:06.470 --> 00:20:09.715
because the display
on the outside,

00:20:09.715 --> 00:20:11.840
in the same case of the
Samsung device, the display

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:15.212
on the outside, I use it
mostly for quick triage,

00:20:15.212 --> 00:20:16.670
if someone sends
me a text message,

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:18.400
and I do need to quickly reply.

00:20:18.400 --> 00:20:22.070
Or maybe I'm dealing
with my notifications.

00:20:22.070 --> 00:20:24.917
But then, when I actually
want to use my phone,

00:20:24.917 --> 00:20:26.000
I'm much more intentional.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.070
Because I physically
open the thing up,

00:20:28.070 --> 00:20:31.923
and so it's much less
that I accidentally,

00:20:31.923 --> 00:20:33.590
30 minutes later, I'm
still on my phone.

00:20:33.590 --> 00:20:35.040
It's much more intentional.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.260
And I actually like
that quite a bit.

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:38.810
And I'm very
productive on it, too.

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:41.030
It's getting a lot
of work done on that.

00:20:41.030 --> 00:20:43.125
Because the extra screen
size really does help.

00:20:43.125 --> 00:20:45.500
FLORENCE ION: Are you using
it with a Bluetooth keyboard?

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:47.240
Are you doing the
whole little [CLICK]??

00:20:47.240 --> 00:20:52.000
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah, just a
on-screen keyboard works great.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.000
FLORENCE ION: All right.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.292
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: So I'm
pretty bullish on foldables,

00:20:55.292 --> 00:20:57.610
in general, not talking
about any specific OEMs,

00:20:57.610 --> 00:20:58.730
but just in general.

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:02.230
As a concept, I don't think
it's going to be a fad.

00:21:02.230 --> 00:21:03.890
It will take a few
years, obviously.

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:06.500
A, they're very
expensive right now,

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:11.453
and it's not yet available
commercially to buy yet.

00:21:11.453 --> 00:21:13.370
So it's going to take a
while for these things

00:21:13.370 --> 00:21:16.590
to become more mainstream.

00:21:16.590 --> 00:21:19.260
But I think they will.

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:20.948
Remember 3D TVs?

00:21:20.948 --> 00:21:21.990
You would go to a store--

00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:22.740
FLORENCE ION: Yes.

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:24.923
I remember the three
CESes of the 3D TVs.

00:21:24.923 --> 00:21:26.090
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Exactly.

00:21:26.090 --> 00:21:27.140
I don't think it's
going to be like that.

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:29.557
I think it's going to actually
be a thing that a lot of us

00:21:29.557 --> 00:21:31.270
will be using.

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:33.440
FLORENCE ION: Honestly,
I feel like everybody's

00:21:33.440 --> 00:21:35.360
feeling the same way
about foldable phones,

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:37.410
just this is a thing
that is going to happen,

00:21:37.410 --> 00:21:39.700
and a lot of buzz around
it, a lot of people excited.

00:21:39.700 --> 00:21:41.750
I was surprised
by it, but I also

00:21:41.750 --> 00:21:44.570
think it's interesting how
quickly Android adopted

00:21:44.570 --> 00:21:47.060
the idea of the foldable
to make it say, well, this

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:48.882
is happening, so there you go.

00:21:48.882 --> 00:21:50.340
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
And by the way,

00:21:50.340 --> 00:21:54.800
that is one of the benefits,
if I may, of Android.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:55.730
It's open source.

00:21:55.730 --> 00:21:57.440
You all know this.

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:00.920
And so foldables
or anytime there's

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:04.880
a big disruption or a new
idea or a new technology,

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:06.770
just the open source
nature of Android

00:22:06.770 --> 00:22:09.590
and how manufacturers can
take it and modify it and do

00:22:09.590 --> 00:22:13.390
what they want to it,
while remaining compatible,

00:22:13.390 --> 00:22:14.880
is an advantage
for the platform.

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:17.172
So that's why you're seeing
foldables first on Android.

00:22:17.172 --> 00:22:18.590
You're seeing 5G
first on Android.

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:21.252
You saw 4G first on Android.

00:22:21.252 --> 00:22:23.210
We talked about it a
little bit at the keynote,

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:25.370
a lot of firsts on Android.

00:22:25.370 --> 00:22:28.040
And that's not just bragging.

00:22:28.040 --> 00:22:30.290
It's just pointing
out the benefits

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:33.900
of how we've developed the
system and the ecosystem.

00:22:33.900 --> 00:22:36.360
Of course, that means a little
more burden in some ways,

00:22:36.360 --> 00:22:38.360
depending on how you look
at it, for developers.

00:22:38.360 --> 00:22:41.030
Because you're like, oh god,
there's yet another thing.

00:22:41.030 --> 00:22:42.920
But it's also an
opportunity for you

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:44.600
to be able to do
interesting things

00:22:44.600 --> 00:22:46.700
for various different
types of devices.

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:49.825
And it might unleash
new use cases for you.

00:22:49.825 --> 00:22:51.200
FLORENCE ION: It
seems like a lot

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.033
of the tools that are
offered for developers

00:22:53.033 --> 00:22:55.220
are very thoughtful.

00:22:55.220 --> 00:22:59.990
Especially, I've noticed
a lot of things being,

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:01.550
not necessarily sequestered.

00:23:01.550 --> 00:23:04.640
But so many little
pieces make up

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:08.720
the OS now to just make it
easy to put in the right puzzle

00:23:08.720 --> 00:23:11.510
piece when it needs to
be shined and cleaned,

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:12.532
to offer a metaphor.

00:23:12.532 --> 00:23:14.240
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Yeah, well mainline--

00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:16.407
I don't know if you literally
mean it in this sense.

00:23:16.407 --> 00:23:19.100
But yeah, we're trying to
modulize the operating system

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:20.550
more.

00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:21.740
There are benefits.

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:23.990
There are benefits from
a security standpoint,

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:25.430
update-ability standpoint.

00:23:25.430 --> 00:23:27.405
Frankly, there's also
benefits just from--

00:23:27.405 --> 00:23:29.280
sorry, this is a little
bit inside baseball--

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:31.280
but within the group.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:32.090
It's easier for us.

00:23:32.090 --> 00:23:33.950
If things are more
modular, it's just

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:37.760
like your code, modular code, is
easier to maintain and release,

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:38.267
and so on.

00:23:38.267 --> 00:23:39.350
FLORENCE ION: Copy, paste.

00:23:39.350 --> 00:23:42.317
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah,
so there's benefits there.

00:23:42.317 --> 00:23:44.150
And so we're definitely
moving more and more

00:23:44.150 --> 00:23:46.490
into that direction for sure.

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:49.350
FLORENCE ION: All
right, switching gears,

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:53.130
you are a big user of Chrome
OS, and you are overseeing it.

00:23:53.130 --> 00:23:55.580
So Chrome OS has really
increased in popularity

00:23:55.580 --> 00:23:56.810
in the last couple of years.

00:23:56.810 --> 00:24:00.440
And I personally see a lot
more of it out in the wilds.

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:02.620
And I'm using it
daily to do my work.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:03.870
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Thank you.

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:04.412
That's great.

00:24:04.412 --> 00:24:08.497
FLORENCE ION: Well, it helps
that it's being worked on.

00:24:08.497 --> 00:24:10.580
So can you talk a little
bit about the trajectory?

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:13.320
Because I mean,
people want to know,

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:17.600
what is the future of
Chrome OS, and especially

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:19.088
about Chrome OS's
favorite color,

00:24:19.088 --> 00:24:20.130
which I heard is fuchsia?

00:24:23.180 --> 00:24:24.770
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: That's yeah.

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:25.550
Wow.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:26.360
You predicted this.

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:29.000
By the way, Flo and I
were talking earlier,

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:30.010
and I was like, what
are you going to ask me,

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:30.968
like my favorite color?

00:24:30.968 --> 00:24:32.900
And she's like, as
long as it's fuchsia.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:35.310
So she's been trying to get
this in, and I guess, yeah.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:36.060
FLORENCE ION: Yes.

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:38.600
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: So we can
talk about future in a second.

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:40.960
Chrome OS, I'm very
excited about, actually.

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:43.550
Of course, I'm
going to say that.

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:44.990
But I genuinely--

00:24:44.990 --> 00:24:47.840
I think Chrome OS
has a real shot,

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:49.730
just to step back for a second.

00:24:49.730 --> 00:24:55.445
I think it was developed
in the modern age.

00:24:55.445 --> 00:24:58.190
There are many other
computing systems

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.773
available for those
form factors, PCs.

00:25:01.773 --> 00:25:04.190
But I think Chrome OS had the
advantage of being developed

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:06.050
in a modern age-- again,
similar to Android,

00:25:06.050 --> 00:25:09.200
where we were able to learn
from some of the past.

00:25:09.200 --> 00:25:12.830
And so security is one of
the most important things,

00:25:12.830 --> 00:25:15.950
and a lot of technology is built
into Chrome OS around that.

00:25:15.950 --> 00:25:18.410
The statelessness, the
stability, the speed,

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:23.940
the four Ss makes it a really
interesting operating system,

00:25:23.940 --> 00:25:26.670
I think, for the
future of computing.

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:30.350
And so we're investing
a lot in Chrome OS.

00:25:30.350 --> 00:25:31.730
I think we have a real shot.

00:25:31.730 --> 00:25:33.230
Commercially, it's
been doing great.

00:25:33.230 --> 00:25:35.605
You said, you know you're
starting to see a lot of people

00:25:35.605 --> 00:25:36.620
use Chrome OS.

00:25:36.620 --> 00:25:40.100
I see that too, which I'm
super excited to see that.

00:25:40.100 --> 00:25:42.950
The PC industry has
been generally flat.

00:25:42.950 --> 00:25:45.660
Chrome OS has been
growing like crazy.

00:25:45.660 --> 00:25:49.252
In Q4 of 2018 in the US,
we were a little over 20%.

00:25:49.252 --> 00:25:50.960
FLORENCE ION: I remember
that stat, yeah.

00:25:50.960 --> 00:25:52.850
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
And so we're growing.

00:25:52.850 --> 00:25:54.240
We're growing significantly.

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:57.710
And by bringing the Play
Store-- and there's also,

00:25:57.710 --> 00:26:00.110
if you're a web developer,
obviously, PWAs,

00:26:00.110 --> 00:26:03.830
and we have a lot of ideas on
how we can make web apps feel

00:26:03.830 --> 00:26:07.430
like native apps, whatever
that means, on Chrome OS,

00:26:07.430 --> 00:26:10.460
as well-- so the
best of both worlds,

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:13.130
with the goal of making
this something that people

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:16.792
can use every day as their main
and maybe even only-- like,

00:26:16.792 --> 00:26:17.500
that's what I do.

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:19.370
I use a Chromebook--

00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:22.830
I use a Pixel Slate,
for what it's worth--

00:26:22.830 --> 00:26:24.935
every day as my
primary and only PC.

00:26:24.935 --> 00:26:26.810
And then, of course, I
have my Android phones

00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:30.660
with me for the
mobile scenarios.

00:26:30.660 --> 00:26:33.260
And I think a lot of people,
a lot of you especially,

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:34.920
should be able to
do that already.

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:36.795
And we want pretty much
everyone in the world

00:26:36.795 --> 00:26:38.550
to be able to do that, as well.

00:26:38.550 --> 00:26:40.640
So developer support,
your support of Chrome OS,

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:42.270
is really, really important.

00:26:42.270 --> 00:26:44.750
Like I said, it's
a growing segment,

00:26:44.750 --> 00:26:46.322
so really interesting stuff.

00:26:46.322 --> 00:26:48.530
And I think we can do some
pretty interesting things.

00:26:48.530 --> 00:26:54.190
I feel like the
difference between--

00:26:54.190 --> 00:26:55.960
remember when tablets
first came out,

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:58.055
everyone predicted
the death of a PC?

00:26:58.055 --> 00:26:59.858
They were like, well,
PCs are going away.

00:26:59.858 --> 00:27:01.150
Tablets are going to take over.

00:27:01.150 --> 00:27:03.490
But that really hasn't happened.

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:08.170
Tablets are popular, too, but
PCs are still around, too.

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:10.690
So it wasn't a mutually
exclusive thing.

00:27:10.690 --> 00:27:13.540
And so I think PCs
are going to continue

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:16.180
to be important
in people's lives,

00:27:16.180 --> 00:27:18.430
and I feel like we can do
some very interesting things

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:23.890
around blending touch and
traditional PCs, [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:27.220
keyboards, detachable
devices, new experiences.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:30.190
And so you're starting to see
us dabble in that a little bit,

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:32.980
and we'll continue
to invest there.

00:27:32.980 --> 00:27:35.230
FLORENCE ION: There's a lot
of little usability tweaks

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:37.670
that you can really
take off from there.

00:27:37.670 --> 00:27:38.962
So back to this Fuchsia thing--

00:27:38.962 --> 00:27:40.712
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Oh yeah, that's right.

00:27:40.712 --> 00:27:41.580
I forgot about it.

00:27:41.580 --> 00:27:42.540
Yes.

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:44.540
FLORENCE ION: Can you
tell us anything about it?

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:45.832
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER: Yeah, sure.

00:27:45.832 --> 00:27:48.700
FLORENCE ION: What's
the ethos behind it?

00:27:48.700 --> 00:27:51.453
What do we have to look forward
to as users of these platforms?

00:27:51.453 --> 00:27:52.870
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Good question.

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:54.750
So Fuchsia, for those of you--

00:27:54.750 --> 00:27:56.500
there might be one
person in this room who

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:57.760
doesn't know what Fuchsia is.

00:27:57.760 --> 00:27:59.263
Has everyone heard of Fuchsia?

00:27:59.263 --> 00:28:00.430
Who hasn't heard of Fuchsia?

00:28:00.430 --> 00:28:01.410
Don't be embarrassed
if you haven't.

00:28:01.410 --> 00:28:02.118
OK, a few people.

00:28:05.320 --> 00:28:07.630
Google has many
projects underway,

00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:09.880
and we're a technology
company, so we

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:13.170
invest in various technologies
and experiment, and so on.

00:28:13.170 --> 00:28:15.550
And some of those
experiments and investments

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:18.190
we do in the public
as an open source

00:28:18.190 --> 00:28:19.660
or as open source projects.

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:20.720
Fuchsia is one of them.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.180
So it's an open source
project by Google,

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:28.210
and it's an investment by us
in modernizing and trying out

00:28:28.210 --> 00:28:31.420
new concepts around
operating systems.

00:28:31.420 --> 00:28:36.265
So naturally, a lot
of people assume,

00:28:36.265 --> 00:28:37.900
well, it's a new OS
from Google, so it

00:28:37.900 --> 00:28:40.570
must be the future of
the one OS from Google.

00:28:40.570 --> 00:28:42.040
But that's not
how we look at it.

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:45.650
We look at it as a place where
we can try out new ideas.

00:28:45.650 --> 00:28:49.102
And so whenever you
see someone saying,

00:28:49.102 --> 00:28:50.560
oh, here's a phone
running Fuchsia,

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:52.360
that's really not our goal.

00:28:52.360 --> 00:28:55.780
It's not about replacing
Android or replacing Chrome OS.

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:57.580
It is about learning
new technologies.

00:28:57.580 --> 00:28:59.590
And maybe Fuchsia
can be launched

00:28:59.590 --> 00:29:01.977
on certain form factors,
different form factors.

00:29:01.977 --> 00:29:04.560
There are all kinds of devices
that require operating systems.

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:06.590
It's not just phones and PCs.

00:29:06.590 --> 00:29:09.070
And in the world of IoT,
there are an increasing number

00:29:09.070 --> 00:29:11.200
of devices that require
operating systems

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:13.090
and new runtimes, and so on.

00:29:13.090 --> 00:29:16.000
So I think there's a lot of
room for multiple operating

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.120
systems with different
strengths and specialization.

00:29:19.120 --> 00:29:20.880
So Fuchsia is one
of those things.

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:21.722
And so stay tuned.

00:29:21.722 --> 00:29:22.930
We'll continue working on it.

00:29:22.930 --> 00:29:25.708
And we enjoy that you
love the intrigue in it,

00:29:25.708 --> 00:29:27.250
but there's really
not much intrigue.

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:28.470
It's just more [INAUDIBLE].

00:29:28.470 --> 00:29:31.140
FLORENCE ION: Intrigue makes
being a user of these things

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:35.780
fun, because it's much safer
than other types of gossip,

00:29:35.780 --> 00:29:38.570
in some cases.

00:29:38.570 --> 00:29:41.110
So back to Chrome OS
just as a platform,

00:29:41.110 --> 00:29:45.940
are we seeing it go more the
way of the Mac and Windows

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:48.580
in terms of usability
and compatibility

00:29:48.580 --> 00:29:49.788
and just like what it can do?

00:29:49.788 --> 00:29:51.330
HIROSHI LOCKHEIMER:
Yeah, we're going

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:53.080
to be better than those things.

00:29:53.080 --> 00:29:55.210
No, honestly, I think
this is what I'm saying.

00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:58.870
I really do think
Chrome OS has a lot

00:29:58.870 --> 00:30:02.020
of the guts of being the
future of the next generation

00:30:02.020 --> 00:30:02.702
of computing.

00:30:02.702 --> 00:30:03.910
We need your support, though.

00:30:03.910 --> 00:30:06.457
We need the use cases,
and we need that.

00:30:06.457 --> 00:30:07.540
I think you all know this.

00:30:07.540 --> 00:30:10.260
People don't buy products
for the operating system.

00:30:10.260 --> 00:30:12.190
But much as an operating
system provider,

00:30:12.190 --> 00:30:14.650
I want to think that way, the
reality is people buy devices

00:30:14.650 --> 00:30:16.150
and products,
because of what they

00:30:16.150 --> 00:30:19.700
can do with it, which is where
you come into the picture.

00:30:19.700 --> 00:30:24.070
And so I think, with the
right set of applications,

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:27.130
it really has the ability
to be the next generation

00:30:27.130 --> 00:30:31.660
of this touch and
keyboard-melded experience,

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:33.640
with new types of form
factors, whether they're

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:36.450
detachables or other things
that haven't been invented yet.

00:30:36.450 --> 00:30:37.835
So yeah, I think it is.

